<section class="section">
  <div class="shell narrow">
    <p class="eyebrow">Questions</p>
    <h2>The fine print, in plain English.</h2>
    <details class="faq">
      <summary>Will it work with my website builder?</summary>
      <p>Yes. If your builder lets you paste an HTML snippet (WordPress, Squarespace, Wix, Webflow, Shopify, GoDaddy, and hand-coded sites all do), the widget works. It isolates its own styles, so it can’t clash with your theme.</p>
    </details>
    <details class="faq">
      <summary>Are the quotes binding?</summary>
      <p>No — they’re estimates built from rates you set, and the result label is yours to word (“Estimated cost”, “Starting from”, whatever fits how you sell). You control every number in the math.</p>
    </details>
    <details class="faq">
      <summary>Where do the leads go?</summary>
      <p>Into your QuoteKit dashboard the instant they’re submitted, with a chart of leads over time and CSV export. Turn on alerts to get an email for each new lead.</p>
    </details>
    <details class="faq">
      <summary>What happens if I cancel?</summary>
      <p>The widget on your site pauses and shows a quiet “temporarily unavailable” note. Your account, calculators, and leads stay intact — re-publish on the Free plan (with the badge) or resubscribe and it comes right back.</p>
    </details>
  </div>
</section>

